:"1252","1230":"1230","1130":"1130","Devon, England":"Devon, Anglie"},"da":{"1175–April 1230":"1175–april 1230","1175–1230":"1175–1230","1175–Female":"1175–Afdød","–1252":"–1252","1125–1202":"1125–1202","1130–Female":"1130–Afdød","1215":"1215","1202":"1202","1224":"1224","1125":"1125","April 1230":"april 1230","1175":"1175","1252":"1252","1230":"1230","1130":"1130","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"nl":{"1175–April 1230":"1175–april 1230","1175–1230":"1175–1230","1175–Female":"1175–Overleden","–1252":"–1252","1125–1202":"1125–1202","1130–Female":"1130–Overleden","1215":"1215","1202":"1202","1224":"1224","1125":"1125","April 1230":"april 1230","1175":"1175","1252":"1252","1230":"1230","1130":"1130","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"1175–April 1230":"1175–April 1230","1175–1230":"1175–1230","1175–Female":"1175–Deceased","–1252":"–1252","1125–1202":"1125–1202","1130–Female":"1130–Deceased","1215":"1215","1202":"1202","1224":"1224","1125":"1125","April 1230":"April 1230","1175":"1175","1252":"1252","1230":"1230","1130":"1130","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kelly","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Kieran, Aileen, John Patrick, Siobhan, Liam, Brigid, Donovan, Eamon, Parnell, Aidan, Clancy.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Ceallaigh</b>, or, in some areas, <b>Mac Ceallaigh</b> ‘descendant (or son) of <i>Ceallach</i>’, an ancient Irish personal name, originally a byname meaning ‘bright-headed’, later understood as ‘frequenting churches’ (Irish <i>ceall</i>). There are several early Irish saints who bore this name. <i>Kelly</i> is now the most common of all surnames in Ireland.","Scottish: habitational name from either the lands of Kelly, near Arbroath (Angus), Kellie in Carnbee (Fife), or Kelly in Methlick (Aberdeenshire). Each of these placenames is from Pictish <i>celli</i> or Gaelic <i>coille</i> ‘wood’ + the placename forming suffix <i>-in</i>. Alternatively, from the lands of Kelloe in the barony of Hume (Berwickshire), whose name is of uncertain origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Kelley","meanings":["Irish (Offaly) and English: variant of   Kelly  ."]},{"name":"Kilkelly","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Bridie.","Irish (Galway): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Ceallaigh</b> ‘son of the devotee of (Saint) Ceallach’ (see   Kelly  )."]},{"name":"Killeen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Donovan, Kieran, Liam.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Cillín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cillín</i>’, a pet form of the personal name <i>Ceallach</i> (see   Kelly  ). The name was borne by various early Irish saints, including the leader of a 7th-century mission to Franconia and Thuringia, hence the popularity of the personal name   Kilian   in medieval central Europe."]},{"name":"Kellis","meanings":["Scottish: patronymic based on   Kelly   as a personal name. Compare   Kellison  .","Greek: descriptive nickname for a bald man, from <i>kelis</i> ‘bald’, a word of Turkish origin (from <i>kel</i> ‘bald’).","History: As a surname of Scottish origin, this has been established in NC since the 18th century."]},{"name":"Kellie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Kelly  ."]},{"name":"Kellison","meanings":["Scottish: patronymic based on   Kelly   as a personal name."]}]},{"name":"Warren","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is of Norman origin, a coalescence of two different surnames, one derived from a Germanic personal name based on the element <i>war(in)</i> ‘guard’ and the other from a place in Normandy called <i>La Varenne</i> ‘the game park’. The Norman personal name survived at least into the 17th century in Yorkshire, where it was particularly associated with the Scargill family. In America this name has sometimes been chosen in honour of  General Joseph Warren , the first hero of the American Revolution, who was killed at  Bunker Hill  (  1775 ). Among modern influences on the choice of the name has been the film actor  Warren Beatty  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":40,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":49,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Warren de Kelly was born in 1175, in Devon, England, his father, William de Kelly, was 51 and his mother, Mrs. William de Kelly, was 46. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Warren de Kelly. He died in April 1230, in his hometown, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1175–April 1230":"1175–aprill 1230","1175–1230":"1175–1230","1175–Female":"1175–Surnud","–1252":"–1252","1125–1202":"1125–1202","1130–Female":"1130–Surnud","1215":"1215","1202":"1202","1224":"1224","1125":"1125","April 1230":"aprill 1230","1175":"1175